00:00:02.410 --> 00:00:04.338
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.338 --> 00:00:08.194
[CLICKING]

00:00:10.795 --> 00:00:12.420
SCOTT HUGHES: So
we're switching gears.

00:00:12.420 --> 00:00:14.440
We're done with the large scale
structure of the universe.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:16.079
Now we're done with cosmology.

00:00:16.079 --> 00:00:18.480
And I'm going to move
into the topic that

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:25.110
will dominate the last
several lectures of 8.962.

00:00:25.110 --> 00:00:28.730
Let's look at how to
construct the spacetime

00:00:28.730 --> 00:00:31.310
of a compact body.

00:00:31.310 --> 00:00:33.290
In particular, we're
going to start by focusing

00:00:33.290 --> 00:00:36.560
on a compact spherical body.

00:00:44.310 --> 00:00:47.210
What I mean by compact-- so
spherical, I hope, is clear--

00:00:47.210 --> 00:00:51.030
but what I mean by compact
is that the body occupies

00:00:51.030 --> 00:00:52.830
a finite spatial region.

00:01:06.030 --> 00:01:11.340
And it has a surface with
an exterior that is vacuum.

00:01:15.890 --> 00:01:17.880
So what I'm going
to do is design

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:20.110
some kind of a spacetime.

00:01:20.110 --> 00:01:22.170
I'm imagining that
there is a source that

00:01:22.170 --> 00:01:23.580
fills some compact region.

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:26.430
I'm going to make it
strictly symmetric.

00:01:26.430 --> 00:01:29.370
And the exterior of the source
will be t mu nu equals 0.

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:37.330
So if you think about
this, this is telling you

00:01:37.330 --> 00:01:39.970
that if it's
spherically symmetric,

00:01:39.970 --> 00:01:44.150
your metric can only
depend on radius.

00:01:44.150 --> 00:01:46.840
And so the most
general form, at least

00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:49.210
for a static spherically
symmetric spacetime--

00:01:49.210 --> 00:01:51.100
we'll talk a little
bit about a few things

00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:54.190
related to non-static
situations a little bit later.

00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:02.140
So the most general static
form of a spherically symmetric

00:02:02.140 --> 00:02:12.410
compact body tells me
that I can write my metric

00:02:12.410 --> 00:02:16.930
as some function of r, which
for reasons of convenience

00:02:16.930 --> 00:02:23.220
I will write that is e
to the 2 phi, t squared.

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:28.780
Some other function
of r, dr squared.

00:02:32.790 --> 00:02:36.330
And then some function of
r times my angular sector.

00:02:41.758 --> 00:02:43.550
You might wonder why
there's no cross-term.

00:02:43.550 --> 00:02:45.383
In particular, why can't
I have a cross-term

00:02:45.383 --> 00:02:47.990
between my dt and my dr?

00:02:47.990 --> 00:02:50.325
I have a few lines
on this in my notes.

00:02:50.325 --> 00:02:51.950
I won't go through
them in detail here,

00:02:51.950 --> 00:02:53.300
but I'll just describe.

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:55.070
Basically, what you
find is that if there

00:02:55.070 --> 00:02:57.980
is a cross-term between,
say, the t and the r pieces,

00:02:57.980 --> 00:03:01.100
you can get rid of it by a
coordinate transformation.

00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:03.230
This way of doing
things so that it

00:03:03.230 --> 00:03:08.530
is diagonal amounts to choosing
a good time coordinate.

00:03:08.530 --> 00:03:10.730
We can simplify
the angular sector

00:03:10.730 --> 00:03:13.419
by choosing a good
radial coordinate.

00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:26.590
The word "good" is a
little bit loaded here.

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:27.490
I'm going to
actually in a moment

00:03:27.490 --> 00:03:29.980
describe a slightly different
choice of radial coordinate,

00:03:29.980 --> 00:03:32.350
which is also good, but
for different purposes.

00:03:32.350 --> 00:03:35.500
The one I'm going
to use is one where

00:03:35.500 --> 00:03:41.710
this function that gives
length to the angular sector

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:43.780
is just r squared.

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:52.490
What this means is
that the coordinate r,

00:03:52.490 --> 00:04:01.990
it labels nested
spheres that have

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:09.350
surface area 4 pi r squared.

00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:11.950
So if you imagine
that in this spacetime

00:04:11.950 --> 00:04:16.899
you make a series of
spheres, and each one of them

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:22.120
has an area 4 pi r squared, that
is the r that goes into this.

00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:25.090
Bear in mind-- [CLEARING THROAT]
excuse me-- bear in mind,

00:04:25.090 --> 00:04:26.590
that does not mean--

00:04:26.590 --> 00:04:32.050
let's say I've got one sphere
of radius 4 pi r1 squared,

00:04:32.050 --> 00:04:37.390
and then outside of it a sphere
of radius 4 pi r2 squared.

00:04:37.390 --> 00:04:40.180
That does not mean that the
distance, the proper distance,

00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:42.790
between those two
spheres is r2 minus r1.

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:59.230
So this is unlikely to measure--

00:04:59.230 --> 00:05:01.070
to label radial
distance cleanly.

00:05:01.070 --> 00:05:02.530
In fact, it would
only be the case

00:05:02.530 --> 00:05:05.600
that this cleanly labels
radial distance if the function

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:07.780
lambda were equal to 0.

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:10.190
And as we'll see, that's
generally not the case.

00:05:10.190 --> 00:05:13.453
So whenever we do things
in a curved spacetime,

00:05:13.453 --> 00:05:15.620
things are always going to
get a little bit messier.

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:17.300
And what's nice about
this is at least

00:05:17.300 --> 00:05:21.620
we do have a clean geometric
meaning to the coordinate r.

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:24.410
In fact, before I
move on, this is

00:05:24.410 --> 00:05:33.680
called an areal radius, a radius
simply related to surface area.

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:52.320
So in the end, the
spacetime that I

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:57.540
will be working with in this
lecture takes this form.

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:07.590
And so this is a
choice that is known

00:06:07.590 --> 00:06:10.016
as Schwarzschild coordinates.

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:27.610
We will come back to the name
Schwarzschild before too long.

00:06:27.610 --> 00:06:30.160
As I said, so this is a
particularly good choice

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:31.150
of radial coordinate.

00:06:31.150 --> 00:06:33.080
It'll be very convenient
for what we do.

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:36.250
It's not the only one.

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:38.350
Other coordinate
choices are possible.

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:40.450
And another one that is
quite useful for us--

00:06:42.970 --> 00:06:46.670
we're not going to use it
too much in this lecture--

00:06:46.670 --> 00:06:49.723
is what are called
isotropic coordinates.

00:06:54.460 --> 00:06:57.270
So this is a coordinate
system in which

00:06:57.270 --> 00:07:17.770
you choose a radial coordinate
which I will call r bar,

00:07:17.770 --> 00:07:19.900
such that your line
element looks like this.

00:07:19.900 --> 00:07:21.790
What this does is
this emphasizes

00:07:21.790 --> 00:07:25.600
the fact that we are working
in a coordinate system--

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:29.800
or excuse me-- we're working
in a spacetime in which all

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:33.970
of your spatial slices are
fundamentally isotropic.

00:07:33.970 --> 00:07:38.065
So get far enough away from
this thing, and the three--

00:07:38.065 --> 00:07:39.940
